<a name="virgil"></a>
<center><table cellpadding=5><tr><td>
<img src="thumb/Virgil_thumbnail.jpg" alt="Virgil" width=93 height=130>
<td>
<h2>Virgil<br>(Publius Virgil Maro)<br>(70 - 19 BC)</h2>
</td></tr></table></center>

<p> Virgil was a Roman poet who delighted in nature, but also sought to understand it through natural philosophy (the science of the time). He included weather signs in a handbook of animal husbandry. His work <i>Georgics</i> consisted of some 2000 lines of poetry on agriculture and weather. Here is an excerpt:

<center><i>
<p> What need to tell of autumn's storms and stars,
<br> And wherefore men must watch,
<br> When now the day grows shorter, and more soft the summer's heat?
<br> When Spring the rain-bringer comes rushing down,
<br> Or when the beards of harvest on the plain bristle already ...
</i></center>

<p><center><table border cellspacing=0>
