<p><hr size=2 color="black">

<a name="razi"></a>
<center><table cellpadding=5><tr><td>
<img src="thumb/Razi_thumbnail.jpg" alt="al Razi" width=96 height=123>
<td>
<h2>Razi, Abu-Bakr Muhammad ibn Zakarayya<br>(Rhazes)<br>(860? - 925?)</h2>
</td></tr></table></center>

<p> Al Razi was a Persian physician. Following the tradition that originated with <a href="#hippocrates">Hippocrates</a> and <a href="#galen">Galen</a>, he wrote in his <i>al-Hawi fi al-Tibb</i> that well-balanced and clean air are one essential prerequisite for good health: polluted air would cause diseases in men. <a href="#avicenna">Avicenna</a> in his work <i>al-Qanun fi al-Tibb</i> had much the same idea. One day, al Razi was asked by the Caliph to choose a site for the proposed Adudi Hospital in Baghdad. To find the answer, he sent out several of his students to hang pieces of fresh meat in the different quarters of the city. The next day, the site at which the meat showed the least tendency to putrefaction was chosen to build the hospital.

