</tr></table></center>

<p><hr size=2 color="black">

<a name="farabi"></a>
<center><table cellpadding=5><tr><td>
<img src="thumb/Farabi_thumbnail.jpg" alt="al Farabi" width=71 height=103>
<td>
<h2>al Farabi, Abu al Nasr<br>(870? - 950?)</h2>
</td></tr></table></center>

<p> Al Farabi was an Afghan philosopher and scientist. He wrote such rich commentaries on <a href="#aristotle">Aristotle's</a> physics, meteorology and logic, in addition to a large number of books on subjects of his own original contribution, that he came to be known as the "Second Teacher" (<a href="#aristotle">Aristotle</a> being the first). Some of al Farabi's work paved the way for the later work of <a href="#avicenna">Avicenna</a>.

